    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix itti_send_msg_to_task_locked accessibility and error handling\n\n### Summary\nThe `itti_send_msg_to_task_locked` function was declared as `static inline`, making it inaccessible from other compilation units. When external modules attempted to call this function directly, they encountered linker errors. Additionally, the function lacked proper error handling for invalid parameters and system call failures.\n\nThis fix removes the `static inline` qualifier to make the function externally accessible, adds comprehensive error checking for null pointers and invalid task IDs, and implements proper error handling for system calls. A function declaration has been added to the header file along with documentation clarifying its intended usage.\n\n### Changes\n- `common/utils/ocp_itti/intertask_interface.cpp`: Removed `static inline` qualifier, added null pointer checks, task ID validation, and proper error handling for system calls. Added necessary includes for errno.h and string.h.\n- `common/utils/ocp_itti/intertask_interface.h`: Added function declaration and documentation explaining that this function should only be called when the task queue is already locked.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Attempt to call `itti_send_msg_to_task_locked()` from a source file other than `intertask_interface.cpp`\n2. Observe linker error: \"undefined reference to `itti_send_msg_to_task_locked'\"\n3. When calling with invalid parameters (null message pointer or invalid task ID), the function would previously crash or exhibit undefined behavior\n4. When the eventfd write operation fails, the function would previously crash due to AssertFatal rather than returning an error code\n\n"
}